revision.text:
These evolutionary tree diagrams are presented as having been created by the Royal Paleontological Scriveners, within the world of Monster Hunter. As none of those diagrams have ever appeared in officially localized English media, the names of the taxa below have no official English names.
Each tree diagram is an updated version of the previous diagram. They were released in the following order:
# [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia 1]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia 2]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia G]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia 3]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia (Reprinted Edition)]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - 10th Anniversary Event]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Hunter's Encyclopedia 4]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Festa '16 Event]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Monster Hunter World Iceborne: Official Complete Works]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Monster Hunter Rise: Official Complete Works]] # [[Evolutionary Tree - Monster Hunter Rise Sunbreak: Official Complete Works]]

The Monster Ecology Encyclopedias (モンスター生態全書) are 15 page long Mooks packaged alongside plastic monster figurines that were published from 2005 to 2013. 18 volumes were ultimately released, with a subset of volumes accompanying each of these main series games. The volumes, in order of release, are as follows:
# [[Monster Hunter: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 1 - Rathalos]] # [[Monster Hunter: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 2 - Yian Kut-Ku]] # [[Monster Hunter: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 3 - Rathian]] # [[Monster Hunter: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 4 - Felyne & Melynx]] # [[Monster Hunter 2: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 1 - Yian Garuga]] # [[Monster Hunter 2: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 2 - Blangonga]] # [[Monster Hunter 2: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 3 - Teostra]] # [[Monster Hunter 2: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia Volume 4 - Funky Felyne & Felyne Chef]] # [[Monster Hunter Portable 3rd: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia I - Zinogre]] # [[Monster Hunter Portable 3rd: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia II - Brute Tigrex]] # [[Monster Hunter Portable 3rd: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia III - Duramboros]] # [[Monster Hunter Portable 3rd: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia IV - Green Nargacuga]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia V - Barioth]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia VI - Ivory Lagiacrus]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia VII - Brachydios]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia VIII - Goldbeard Ceadeus]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia IX - Savage Deviljho]] # [[Monster Hunter 3G: Monster Ecology Encyclopedia X - Hallowed Jhen Mohran]]
Each volume featured information on the figurine monster(s) it was packaged with. Volumes also included bonus figurine pieces that could be combined across all of the volumes for a given game to assemble an additional monster. These bonus monster figurines for each of the games, in release order, were:
# Monoblos # Lao-Shan Lung # Amatsu # Stygian Zinogre
The individual pages for the volumes contain more information on the contents of each, but in general they would describe the ecology and anatomy of the featured monster from the perspective of ongoing, in-universe research expeditions. The first 8 volumes also included more information about the setting, even including world maps, while the final 10 volumes were more exclusively focused on monsters.

revision.text:
'''Monster Variations''' refers to phenomenons in which monsters show slight but distinct differences from their regular counterparts, usually making them more formidable opponents. These variations usually fall into two broad categories: *'''Individual variations''' are when only a singular individual monster experience a change during its lifespan that separates it from the other members of its species, with some of these changes being initiated by some affliction-like malady; examples of this are phenomenoms such as [[Variant]]s, [[Deviant]]s, monsters infected by the [[Frenzy Virus]], monsters blighted by the [[Black Blight]], [[Apex]] monsters, [[Afflicted Monsters]], [[Risen Elder Dragons]], and monsters Rage-rayed by [[Oltura]]. *'''Population variations''' are when a smaller population of a given monster species have evolved different adaptations, resulting in them becoming biologically different since birth from their base counterparts: examples of this are the phenomenoms of [[Subspecies]] and [[Rare Species]]. However, this general categorization is not always a perfect match, as for example many early introduced monster variations are labeled as Subspecies despite actually sharing characteristics more akin to Variants.
